# Day 03 - Viewing Files + Finding Files

## Theory
- In DevOps you read log files constantly
- A log file can have millions of lines — you can't open it in notepad
- Use terminal commands to read, search, and filter
- Finding files on a server is a daily task

## Commands Learned

### Viewing Files
| Command | What it does |
|---------|-------------|
| `cat file` | Print entire file (small files only) |
| `less file` | Read file page by page — press q to quit, space for next page |
| `head file` | Show first 10 lines |
| `head -n 20 file` | Show first 20 lines |
| `tail file` | Show last 10 lines |
| `tail -n 50 file` | Show last 50 lines |
| `tail -f file` | LIVE — keep showing new lines as they appear (for logs!) |

### Searching Inside Files (grep)
| Command | What it does |
|---------|-------------|
| `grep "word" file` | Search for word in file, shows matching lines |
| `grep -i "word" f` | Search ignoring uppercase/lowercase |
| `grep -n "word" f` | Search and show line numbers |
| `grep -r "word" .` | Search in ALL files in current folder and subfolders |
| `grep -v "word" f` | Show lines that do NOT contain word |
| `grep -c "word" f` | Count how many lines match |

### Finding Files (find)
| Command | What it does |
|---------|-------------|
| `find / -name "f"` | Find file named f anywhere on system |
| `find . -name "*.sh"` | Find all .sh files in current folder |
| `find . -type f` | Find only files (not folders) |
| `find . -type d` | Find only directories |
| `find . -size +1M` | Find files larger than 1MB |
| `find . -mtime -7` | Find files modified in last 7 days |
| `find . -size +0c -type f` | Find non-empty files |

### Locating Commands
| Command | What it does |
|---------|-------------|
| `which command` | Show where a command is installed |
| `locate filename` | Fast search using database (install: apt install mlocate) |

## Key Takeaways
- `tail -f` is your best friend for watching live logs on production servers — you will use this every day as a DevOps engineer
- `grep -r` searches recursively through all files — great for finding config values
- `grep -v` inverts the search — useful for filtering out noise in logs
- Pipe commands together for power: `grep -v "Line 5" testlog.txt | head`
- `find /etc -name "*.conf" 2>/dev/null | head -10` — finds config files safely

## Script Written Today

**`day03/search_practice.sh`**
```bash
#!/bin/bash
# Search Practice Script - Day 03
# Demonstrates grep and find

# Create a test log file
for i in {1..100}; do
  echo "Line $i: some log data here"
done > testlog.txt

echo "=== First 10 lines ==="
head testlog.txt

echo "=== Last 10 lines ==="
tail testlog.txt

echo "=== Lines containing 'Line 5' ==="
grep "Line 5" testlog.txt

echo "=== Count of lines with 'data' ==="
grep -c "data" testlog.txt

echo "=== Find all .txt files ==="
find . -name "*.txt"

echo "=== Find all .sh files ==="
find . -name "*.sh"
```

